e kanji for &amp;#12375;&amp;#12398;(&amp;#12400;&amp;#12379;&amp;#12427<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  &quot;shinobaseru&quot; (&quot;to walk stealthily&quot;) <br>and the second is the kanji for &amp;#12418;&amp;#12398; &quot;mono&quot; (&quot;person&quot;)<br>as i said, the pronunciation when combined is &quot;Ninja&quot;.<br>__________________________________________________<br><br>The nin character is not &quot;to walk stealthily&quot;. It's comprised of the &quot;sword&quot; character above the &quot;heart&quot; character. In my clan (Togakure Ryu), there are a lot of us who take it to mean &quot;perserverance&quot;. As in &quot;Though the enemy holds his sword menacingly over my heart, I will endure.&quot; I dislike it when people take ninjutsu at face value, because in a lot of ways, our face value isn't always so great. Like the clichÈ definitions of ninjutsu as &quot;the art of invisibility&quot; and such. Me and my friends (jokingly) call it &quot;the art of winning,&quot; but it's not really an art at all. Sorry about that, got off topic while ranting again. Just thought I'd throw in my two cents. <br><br>Btw, if you don't mind changing your theme, why don't you use one of the more exotic ninja weapons, like the shoge? Putting &quot;ninja weapons&quot; or &quot;Togakure&quot; in a search engine should find you something a lot neater than a &quot;knife&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/umaimaipanda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/30/02 9:03:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=713.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://tare-panda2.dhs.org/tarepanda/pictures/taresugokusuki.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How do you say Knifing Ninjas in japanese?</span><hr size=1> actually, i never said the &quot;nin&quot; character was to walk stealthily.  What I said is that it is the character from the verb &quot;shinobaseru&quot;, which <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  is</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  &quot;to walk stealthily&quot;. It can also be used in &quot;shinobiyoru&quot; (&quot;to sneak up&quot;), &quot;shinobikomu&quot; (&quot;to sneak into&quot; (sorta'))and &quot;shinobiashi&quot; (&quot;to tiptoe&quot;).  So while i never said the kanji itself was &quot;to walk stealthily&quot; it is found in a great many compounds which revolve around stealth and sneaking and skulking and all those other cliqued ninja things <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br><br>On another note, while it's true that the radicals for the kanji in question are &quot;sword&quot; and &quot;heart&quot;, there's a limit to the extent to which we can deconstruct kanji components to find meanings.  While I'm certainly not saying that ketsueki's interpretaion is incorrect, would we say then that &quot;omou&quot; évÇ§<br> (to think) has to do with a &quot;field/rice patty&quot; and a &quot;heart&quot;?  (Of course, given some of the convuluted stories i've heard about various kanji origins, i wouldn't put it past plausible!)<br><br>Anyway, I'm definitely not trying start an argument or anything ketsu, i just wanted to clarify that the only reason why i mentioned &quot;to walk stealthily&quot; is so he could look up the character if he wanted to. <p><B> <I>Ask me about microwaving cats for fun and profit! </I> </B><BR>. . . . err, no umm...</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/umaimaipanda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>maimaipanda</A> at: 3/30/02 9:04:58 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uaohjp.showPublicProfile?language=EN>aoh jp</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/30/02 9:24:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=713.topic&index=5>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How do you say Knifing Ninjas in japanese?</span><hr size=1> Ninja was a Japanese secret agent in feudal times (with almost magical powers of stealth and concealment) and years of incessant hard special training was required to become ninja.<br><br>Ninjutsu is not a simple art but was a &quot;specially sophisticated military arts&quot;. The way of using ninjutsu was almost just like that of acrobatics and sometimes quite scientific and chemical. <p>aoh</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uaohjp.showPublicProfile?language=EN>aoh jp</A> at: 3/30/02 9:26:13 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/udedookie.showPublicProfile?language=EN>de dookie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/31/02 10:03:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=713.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How do you say Knifing Ninjas in japanese?</span><hr size=1> Well, thxs a lot for the help guys. Well, I originally intended a direct translation to the word. <p><br><blockquote>Webmaster and proud member of the Knifing Ninjas Clan for Half Life: Counter Strik